00:14:30.448 --> 00:14:33.978
SPP protocol cleared because there was a clear biological

239
00:14:34.068 --> 00:14:37.868
rationale for using menin inhibitors in infants and

240
00:14:37.908 --> 00:14:39.017
children. And

241
00:14:40.828 --> 00:14:44.128
I'm just taking a figure out of a paper that was published with Scott Armstrong

242
00:14:44.148 --> 00:14:47.938
that we were on in 2019, and some of the rationale for going into

243
00:14:48.048 --> 00:14:49.668
pediatric patients is shown here.

244
00:14:49.728 --> 00:14:53.448
This was studies sponsored by the NCI and the

245
00:14:53.828 --> 00:14:57.728
Preclinical Pediatric Testing Consortium, which may have changed its name.

246
00:14:58.008 --> 00:14:59.288
I think it might be called Pivot now.

247
00:14:59.968 --> 00:15:01.088
But this is

248
00:15:03.028 --> 00:15:06.528
a great resource, that's all I can tell you, that the NCI has, that you can

249
00:15:06.588 --> 00:15:10.188
test new agents in rare or unmet needs in

250
00:15:10.968 --> 00:15:13.908
pediatric cancers, and they do a phenomenal job.

251
00:15:13.968 --> 00:15:17.848
And so the picture on the right just shows the results of a study we did

252
00:15:17.888 --> 00:15:20.188
with Dr. Richard Locke at Sydney Children's.

253
00:15:20.848 --> 00:15:24.488
And essentially what we've done here is taken eight pediatric

254
00:15:24.568 --> 00:15:28.118
PDXs. They're all B-ALL PDXs over a range of

255
00:15:28.188 --> 00:15:32.068
translocations. And we've treated these animals for 28

256
00:15:32.108 --> 00:15:34.568
days with rev and then followed them.

257
00:15:34.868 --> 00:15:37.668
So on the chart, you see all the animals that were in the study.

258
00:15:37.728 --> 00:15:41.368
Everybody showed up. And we're looking at any kind of treatment and survival

259
00:15:41.428 --> 00:15:45.388
benefit. And what we noticed right away was that essentially seven out of the

260
00:15:45.448 --> 00:15:49.148
eight PDXs had an obvious and significant survival

261
00:15:49.208 --> 00:15:53.058
benefit, some two to three months, some out to 10 to 12 months, and actually some

262
00:15:53.068 --> 00:15:54.628
of these animals were followed over a year.

263
00:15:55.648 --> 00:15:59.528
And so we obviously had a single agent effect, and so it was compelling rationale

264
00:15:59.568 --> 00:16:02.848
to biologically to go into the younger patients.

265
00:16:03.348 --> 00:16:05.848
And at the bottom is a Philadelphia chromosome positive

266
00:16:07.128 --> 00:16:09.448
leukemia, which shouldn't respond, and it doesn't.

267
00:16:09.488 --> 00:16:13.388
And so I think having this in place was one of the key

268
00:16:13.448 --> 00:16:17.388
drivers for everybody, at least on the scientific rationale side and actually the

269
00:16:17.408 --> 00:16:21.348
preclinical pharmacology side, to take the leap and go ahead

270
00:16:21.388 --> 00:16:24.988
and start honoring some of these SPPs and requests from the

271
00:16:25.008 --> 00:16:26.268
pediatric docs.

272
00:16:28.668 --> 00:16:28.808
So

273
00:16:29.988 --> 00:16:31.868
just overlooking everything that we've done here.

274
00:16:31.908 --> 00:16:34.848
So these single patient protocols became very important.

275
00:16:35.148 --> 00:16:38.508
We quickly established that the exposure across the

276
00:16:38.528 --> 00:16:42.178
different sizes and ages of children was quite

277
00:16:42.268 --> 00:16:45.308
proportional between adults and children.

278
00:16:45.348 --> 00:16:49.008
There was really nothing special about uptake or clearance that changed the PK

279
00:16:49.048 --> 00:16:50.208
of the compound.

280
00:16:52.308 --> 00:16:54.448
It allows to collect a lot of data, and essentially,

281
00:16:55.288 --> 00:16:58.998
once it was consistent, then we were open the enrollment to the patients down to 30

282
00:16:59.248 --> 00:16:59.828
days of age.

283
00:17:01.088 --> 00:17:04.838
These are key things. So, in 2020, as I just said,

284
00:17:04.908 --> 00:17:08.778
we were able to go down to 30 years of age, and then in 2022,

285
00:17:09.268 --> 00:17:13.128
we're actually able to open a study where we're looking at revumenib in

286
00:17:13.189 --> 00:17:15.038
combo with intensive chemotherapy.

287
00:17:15.108 --> 00:17:15.648
Because again,

288
00:17:16.508 --> 00:17:20.449
Richard Locke's lab in Sydney had generated some chemo combo data

289
00:17:20.508 --> 00:17:24.138
with rev and some of these ALLs and also shown, again, really quite

290
00:17:24.168 --> 00:17:28.058
beneficial treatment effects. So at the end of the day, if you look at

291
00:17:28.168 --> 00:17:32.108
when we registered the compound, we had over 130 SPPs

292
00:17:32.178 --> 00:17:35.808
that came with the filing as well. So you can see here 25

293
00:17:35.888 --> 00:17:39.148
infants, 78 children, 29 adolescents.

294
00:17:39.228 --> 00:17:43.008
So it was a pretty heavy lift, I think, on the regulatory side.

295
00:17:43.098 --> 00:17:46.768
They had to do a lot of SPPs, and

296
00:17:47.708 --> 00:17:51.648
so I think they spread the wealth there, and everybody was spending a lot of time

297
00:17:51.708 --> 00:17:55.664
on that, so.So now we've already

298
00:17:55.704 --> 00:17:56.124
got these

299
00:17:57.024 --> 00:18:00.964
patients, or the young patients are already now getting enrolled

300
00:18:01.024 --> 00:18:03.584
in the study. The question is, how do you get drug to them?

301
00:18:03.624 --> 00:18:07.344
Yeah, and what are the kind of hurdles of dealing with a drug

302
00:18:07.904 --> 00:18:08.024
in

303
00:18:09.004 --> 00:18:12.314
a young patient population? I think one of the things you have to realize is that

304
00:18:12.804 --> 00:18:16.504
revumumab is an amine. It's basic. It's a protonated amine.

305
00:18:16.534 --> 00:18:17.144
And I don't know if you

306
00:18:18.264 --> 00:18:20.444
ever dealt with these substances.

307
00:18:20.804 --> 00:18:24.524
Protonated amines tend to be very bitter, and revumumab is no

308
00:18:24.564 --> 00:18:25.944
exception. It does not taste good.

309
00:18:26.024 --> 00:18:26.204
So,

310
00:18:28.024 --> 00:18:29.323
you don't want to taste your drugs usually.

311
00:18:30.024 --> 00:18:30.324
So,

312
00:18:31.184 --> 00:18:34.944
what we needed to do was try to get it into a form that was presentable and that

313
00:18:35.164 --> 00:18:38.724
we could dose accurately into the smaller patients.

314
00:18:38.784 --> 00:18:42.504
And one of the things about being a protonated amine, this actually gave revumumab

315
00:18:42.704 --> 00:18:46.664
some quite good solubility. So, it's soluble at mgs per ml,

316
00:18:46.744 --> 00:18:50.344
many mgs per ml, actually. And so we were able to basically make

317
00:18:51.184 --> 00:18:55.144
accurate concentrations of rev as liquid solutions that really

318
00:18:55.184 --> 00:18:59.004
facilitated the administering, especially into the younger patients that might be,

319
00:18:59.164 --> 00:19:02.864
say, on NG tubes. So we could precisely and accurately deliver

320
00:19:02.904 --> 00:19:06.714
doses to these patients, and be sure that we weren't putting

321
00:19:06.764 --> 00:19:10.424
anybody at risk and that the exposures were really quite proportional to what we

322
00:19:10.464 --> 00:19:11.384
wanted.

323
00:19:12.944 --> 00:19:15.404
We didn't see any difference in the PK in the younger patients.

324
00:19:16.324 --> 00:19:16.634
And then

325
00:19:17.544 --> 00:19:21.084
the last bit of it is actually just a talk about the physicality of the

326
00:19:21.104 --> 00:19:25.004
CMC aspect. So when you think about somebody

327
00:19:25.044 --> 00:19:28.964
says, "I have a crystal and a solid," you think, "Oh, salt. It's really solid.

328
00:19:29.004 --> 00:19:32.964
I can pour it out and it runs well." Well, we had a crystal and solid, but it was

329
00:19:33.024 --> 00:19:35.824
a fluffy, sticky, and not very flowing solid.

330
00:19:35.904 --> 00:19:39.104
So it was not trivial, just mechanically, to deal with it.

331
00:19:39.164 --> 00:19:39.324
So,

332
00:19:40.764 --> 00:19:43.644
I'm going to go through some of the presentations we had clinically, and then just

333
00:19:43.724 --> 00:19:45.904
how they all fit into the overall program.

334
00:19:46.484 --> 00:19:48.344
So we actually started out in capsules.

335
00:19:49.124 --> 00:19:52.894
So basically, there was a revumumab blend in capsules.

336
00:19:53.524 --> 00:19:57.404
And given that it was sticky and fluffy, it actually was staticky and held a static

337
00:19:57.464 --> 00:20:01.304
charge. And so when you were basically doing production, you

338
00:20:01.344 --> 00:20:03.164
basically were building up static charge.

339
00:20:03.184 --> 00:20:06.244
And when they did production, they used to actually walk around with an anti-static

340
00:20:06.324 --> 00:20:09.104
gun to kind of neutralize the charge on the trays.

341
00:20:09.584 --> 00:20:09.824
It's not

342
00:20:11.364 --> 00:20:14.144
funny in some ways, but it is. But anyway.

343
00:20:15.304 --> 00:20:18.364
But the advantage of having these capsules available and knowing about the

344
00:20:18.384 --> 00:20:22.344
solubility of rev is that early on, we used what we

345
00:20:22.384 --> 00:20:24.824
call extemporaneous solutions, essentially.

346
00:20:24.864 --> 00:20:28.804
You know the content in your capsule, so if it's, let's say 115

347
00:20:28.844 --> 00:20:30.124
milligrams, you can put

348
00:20:31.104 --> 00:20:33.424
it in 10 mils, you know it's 11.5 mgs per ml.

349
00:20:33.524 --> 00:20:33.924
So we could

350
00:20:35.344 --> 00:20:39.184
basically use these capsules, discard the shell, and essentially make

351
00:20:39.224 --> 00:20:42.304
up liquid solutions to an accurate concentration.

352
00:20:42.314 --> 00:20:45.663
And in the pharmacy in the hospitals, it was very doable.

353
00:20:45.704 --> 00:20:49.404
And so we also had to do some characterization of those solutions to make sure they

354
00:20:49.424 --> 00:20:53.124
were stable, that the compound didn't oxidize or hydrolyze or anything like that.

355
00:20:53.224 --> 00:20:55.644
So with stability, you go along with that.

356
00:20:55.724 --> 00:20:59.604
So, those are just practical aspects that you need to deal

357
00:20:59.644 --> 00:21:00.984
with when you're putting these things together.

358
00:21:02.044 --> 00:21:05.824
And so at this point now, we are at the point we have a liquid formulation.

359
00:21:06.804 --> 00:21:09.004
A couple of key aspects here, since it does taste bitter.

360
00:21:09.424 --> 00:21:12.584
We spent, actually, it wasn't me, it was actually our CMC group

361
00:21:13.564 --> 00:21:16.124
led by Aaron Marolewsky. They did a really phenomenal job.

362
00:21:17.684 --> 00:21:21.084
To hide the bitter taste, we spent a long time trying to

363
00:21:21.144 --> 00:21:24.844
find a formulation with acceptable excipients which

364
00:21:24.884 --> 00:21:28.004
could hide the taste and be palatable in some way.

365
00:21:28.224 --> 00:21:32.064
And then at the same time, to make a stable or shelf-stable

366
00:21:32.144 --> 00:21:35.844
solution, we had to find a number of preservatives or things that could basically

367
00:21:36.604 --> 00:21:40.324
keep it stable and make sure it didn't oxidize or hydrolyze over time, and it

368
00:21:40.364 --> 00:21:44.334
can have a shelf life that would be easy for, say, 28 days to administer a

369
00:21:44.364 --> 00:21:46.484
drug on one cycle.

370
00:21:47.774 --> 00:21:50.504
And now we've kind of moved ahead with the program.

371
00:21:50.564 --> 00:21:53.484
So we got rid of the capsules during the development.

372
00:21:53.524 --> 00:21:57.104
We replaced them with tablets. Right now, we have two presentations.

373
00:21:57.144 --> 00:22:00.644
We have 110 milligram and 160 milligram tablet.

374
00:22:00.694 --> 00:22:04.324
And realizing that pediatrics, those are still too big.

375
00:22:04.404 --> 00:22:08.284
We actually had a campaign and developed a 25 milligram tablet as well.

376
00:22:08.404 --> 00:22:12.323
So, younger patients who can swallow a tablet can take that, and it also has the

377
00:22:12.344 --> 00:22:16.024
advantage that it can be readily dissolved if needed to

378
00:22:16.184 --> 00:22:18.504
generate a liquid formulation.

379
00:22:21.304 --> 00:22:25.264
So, a few of the lessons that we learned along the way, and I hope maybe they

380
00:22:25.324 --> 00:22:29.094
translate and can help anybody else out there that's in the middle of a development

381
00:22:29.124 --> 00:22:32.784
program or considering a development program in pediatrics.

382
00:22:33.724 --> 00:22:35.284
Engage the regulators early.

383
00:22:36.684 --> 00:22:40.544
Even though we weren't allowed to use children in the original enrollment

384
00:22:40.564 --> 00:22:44.484
criteria, we quickly were able to switch that and open

385
00:22:44.504 --> 00:22:47.804
the trial to younger patients based on data that we were able to generate in

386
00:22:47.844 --> 00:22:51.424
collaboration with the FDA. We basically set all the metrics that they

387
00:22:51.464 --> 00:22:54.724
want. They set the metrics, and we were able to fulfill them, and we basically were

388
00:22:54.784 --> 00:22:57.404
able to change the enrollment at that point.

389
00:22:58.384 --> 00:22:58.944
I think you need to

390
00:22:59.864 --> 00:23:00.604
think creatively.

391
00:23:02.704 --> 00:23:04.244
Not every solution's obvious.

392
00:23:05.824 --> 00:23:09.374
The single-patient protocols ended up being obviously the key for us,

393
00:23:10.044 --> 00:23:13.444
I think, for advancing the program as quickly as we did in the pediatric patients

394
00:23:13.484 --> 00:23:16.944
and collecting those data, not only for safety and PK, but also for

395
00:23:17.504 --> 00:23:21.344
eventual registration. And don't underestimate the

396
00:23:21.384 --> 00:23:21.924
CMC

397
00:23:22.744 --> 00:23:26.144
aspects of this. If you're lucky, like us, your compound is soluble.

398
00:23:26.844 --> 00:23:30.724
You can administer it in an accurate dose that's proportional with the size,

399
00:23:30.804 --> 00:23:34.334
weight of the subjects. But

400
00:23:34.364 --> 00:23:37.704
there may be a little more of a lift if you're doing something

401
00:23:37.744 --> 00:23:41.044
with a solid that's not highly soluble.

402
00:23:41.144 --> 00:23:45.124
So you have to get creative on how to make something that's sort of uniform, and

403
00:23:45.384 --> 00:23:47.824
titratable, and dosable at the same time.

404
00:23:48.164 --> 00:23:51.932
So.And we're going to wrap up

405
00:23:51.952 --> 00:23:53.392
there, and then I'm just basically going to

406
00:23:54.752 --> 00:23:58.112
acknowledge and thank everybody, especially the patients who are enrolled in these

407
00:23:58.172 --> 00:24:00.852
trials, their families, their caregivers.

408
00:24:01.392 --> 00:24:04.492
I'll read this out, actually. Study investigators, study teams, and the clinical

409
00:24:04.532 --> 00:24:08.212
researchers. A phenomenal number of people are involved in this.

410
00:24:08.272 --> 00:24:11.792
And then a number of current and former Syntex employees who helped

411
00:24:12.352 --> 00:24:15.842
get this, not only into the clinic, but to the registration.

412
00:24:16.392 --> 00:24:20.252
And FDA for really highly constructive interactions throughout this entire

413
00:24:20.292 --> 00:24:23.212
process. They were true collaborators all along the way.

414
00:24:23.712 --> 00:24:27.552
And then, all the drug substance and people who make the drug

415
00:24:27.612 --> 00:24:31.412
and helped with dealing with these novel formulations as

416
00:24:31.472 --> 00:24:33.632
well. So, thank you for your time and

417
00:24:35.152 --> 00:24:35.492
that's it.

418
00:24:36.292 --> 00:24:36.772
Questions.

419
00:24:37.352 --> 00:24:37.912
Questions later.

420
00:24:40.462 --> 00:24:47.312
That's

421
00:24:47.352 --> 00:24:47.612
good.

422
00:24:47.621 --> 00:24:50.312
Yeah, I guess.

423
00:24:52.572 --> 00:24:56.482
Hi, good afternoon, and thank you to the AACR Pediatric Cancer Working Group for

424
00:24:56.512 --> 00:24:59.612
having me. So happy to be here. My name is Nicole Dresner.

425
00:24:59.752 --> 00:25:03.532
I'm a pediatric oncologist and the Deputy Director of the Division of

426
00:25:03.592 --> 00:25:05.352
Oncology 2 at the FDA.

427
00:25:06.172 --> 00:25:09.872
I'm going to give a brief overview of the regulatory considerations that we

428
00:25:09.912 --> 00:25:13.772
apply when we are reviewing proposals for early phase and later

429
00:25:13.832 --> 00:25:16.312
phase pediatric cancer trials.

430
00:25:18.012 --> 00:25:18.992
These are my disclosures.

431
00:25:22.252 --> 00:25:26.212
So back in 1995, the American Academy of Pediatrics published

432
00:25:26.292 --> 00:25:30.272
guidelines on the ethical conduct of studies to evaluate drugs in

433
00:25:30.292 --> 00:25:33.822
pediatric populations, noting that there is a moral imperative

434
00:25:34.692 --> 00:25:38.452
to formally study drugs in children so that they can enjoy equal

435
00:25:38.532 --> 00:25:41.452
access to existing as well as new therapeutic agents.

436
00:25:42.092 --> 00:25:45.672
These guidelines were updated in 2010, after the passage of some of the

437
00:25:45.732 --> 00:25:48.052
legislation I'll discuss later in the presentation.

438
00:25:48.732 --> 00:25:52.612
And the authors then reiterated the importance of formal research, stating

439
00:25:52.652 --> 00:25:56.592
that the performance of research studies to evaluate drugs in children is

440
00:25:56.632 --> 00:26:00.442
critical for determining the safety and efficacy of medications in children.

441
00:26:00.852 --> 00:26:04.522
Without this type of research, they went on, medication use in children will be

442
00:26:04.552 --> 00:26:08.382
limited to extrapolation from adult studies or off-label use for

443
00:26:08.412 --> 00:26:12.142
indications that have not been studied in children, thereby putting them at

444
00:26:12.192 --> 00:26:14.692
increased risk of adverse effects.

445
00:26:14.702 --> 00:26:18.312
These notions really underpin the regulatory considerations that we

446
00:26:18.352 --> 00:26:22.302
apply to all phases of drug development for children with cancer to

447
00:26:22.352 --> 00:26:26.242
uphold the rigorous standards of safety and efficacy while accounting

448
00:26:26.272 --> 00:26:29.892
for the flexibility that is often required for rare diseases with a

449
00:26:29.932 --> 00:26:31.332
high unmet medical need.

450
00:26:34.672 --> 00:26:38.412
So who are the FDA staff reviewing pediatric oncology drug

451
00:26:38.512 --> 00:26:42.392
development? The Oncology Center of Excellence, or OCE,

452
00:26:42.432 --> 00:26:46.082
was established in 2017 to facilitate the development and

453
00:26:46.192 --> 00:26:49.942
clinical review of oncology products by uniting scientific

454
00:26:50.072 --> 00:26:53.772
experts across the FDA's product centers to conduct

455
00:26:53.812 --> 00:26:56.882
expedited review of drugs, biologics, and devices.

456
00:26:57.532 --> 00:27:01.282
Pediatric oncologists and other review staff with expertise in

457
00:27:01.292 --> 00:27:04.602
evaluating pediatric oncology therapeutics, including non-clinical

458
00:27:04.672 --> 00:27:08.312
pharmacologists, are incorporated throughout CDER and CBER

459
00:27:08.322 --> 00:27:12.152
divisions, overseeing the full spectrum of pediatric cancer indications, as

460
00:27:12.192 --> 00:27:13.052
shown on the slide.

461
00:27:13.972 --> 00:27:17.892
As I mentioned, my division, Division of Oncology 2, reviews drugs and some

462
00:27:17.912 --> 00:27:21.812
biologics for pediatric solid tumors, neuro-oncology, and rare

463
00:27:21.852 --> 00:27:22.272
tumors.

464
00:27:23.912 --> 00:27:27.512
So during this talk, I'm going to discuss the unique regulatory considerations for

465
00:27:27.552 --> 00:27:29.681
early pediatric oncology drug development.

466
00:27:30.272 --> 00:27:34.072
I will next review considerations for the inclusion of adolescent patients in

467
00:27:34.132 --> 00:27:36.012
adult oncology clinical trials.

468
00:27:36.872 --> 00:27:40.852
I will discuss specific early phase trial design elements that may facilitate

469
00:27:40.912 --> 00:27:44.092
drug development for pediatric patients, and I will discuss some of the

470
00:27:44.132 --> 00:27:48.092
legislation that has affected pediatric oncology drug development

471
00:27:48.152 --> 00:27:48.552
to date.

472
00:27:50.392 --> 00:27:54.382
Inherent to pediatric drug development is the notion that information and data from

473
00:27:54.392 --> 00:27:58.372
properly evaluated medicines should be assessed in a timely manner to ensure

474
00:27:58.412 --> 00:28:00.492
the proper use of medicinal products.

475
00:28:00.512 --> 00:28:04.352
And this includes, as you just heard, the development of pediatric formulations to

476
00:28:04.392 --> 00:28:07.612
ensure access across the entire relevant age spectrum.

477
00:28:09.811 --> 00:28:13.632
While some principles that underlie adult drug development apply to children,

478
00:28:13.672 --> 00:28:15.942
there are unique considerations for the development of

479
00:28:16.872 --> 00:28:18.632
drugs for pediatric populations.

480
00:28:19.072 --> 00:28:22.592
Beginning with non-clinical study, the requirements for data submission

481
00:28:22.612 --> 00:28:26.042
depend on whether the pediatric trial is also a first-in-human trial.

482
00:28:26.652 --> 00:28:30.432
If the pediatric trial is not first in human, additional toxicology

483
00:28:30.472 --> 00:28:33.432
studies prior to initiating a clinical trial are often not

484
00:28:33.452 --> 00:28:37.212
necessary. And juvenile animal toxicology studies are

485
00:28:37.252 --> 00:28:40.722
generally only required if drug development is exclusively in

486
00:28:40.732 --> 00:28:44.152
pediatrics, or if there are potential long-term development

487
00:28:44.332 --> 00:28:48.192
toxicities that are anticipated by the drug's mechanism of action

488
00:28:48.712 --> 00:28:52.232
or earlier studies. Ideally, for a clinical

489
00:28:52.272 --> 00:28:53.112
development program,

490
00:28:54.612 --> 00:28:58.412
for pediatric patients should be adequate to support an evaluation of dosing,

491
00:28:58.472 --> 00:29:02.382
safety, and efficacy and include plans for pediatric formulation

492
00:29:02.432 --> 00:29:06.052
development. For both adult patients and pediatric patients, the

493
00:29:06.152 --> 00:29:10.082
standard for drug approval is the same and requires a demonstration of

494
00:29:10.112 --> 00:29:14.032
substantial evidence of effectiveness through adequate and well-controlled trials.

495
00:29:15.852 --> 00:29:19.712
There are several other regulatory considerations that are unique to early-phase

496
00:29:19.752 --> 00:29:21.452
pediatric oncology drug development.

497
00:29:22.372 --> 00:29:26.292
Although patient populations are small, the pharmacokinetics of a drug should

498
00:29:26.352 --> 00:29:30.212
be evaluated over the entire pediatric age range in which the agent will be

499
00:29:30.352 --> 00:29:34.192
used. Initial pediatric study plans for early pediatric drug

500
00:29:34.272 --> 00:29:38.212
development should address the entire pediatric age range from birth

501
00:29:38.252 --> 00:29:42.072
to less than 17 years of age, though plans may include justification for

502
00:29:42.112 --> 00:29:45.672
waiver of clinical study in a particular age group if studies in that

503
00:29:45.692 --> 00:29:49.562
population would be infeasible. Typical age groupings are listed on

504
00:29:49.592 --> 00:29:52.680
the slideAnd the FDA

505
00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:56.560
generally requests that sponsors propose a reasonable minimum

506
00:29:56.600 --> 00:30:00.380
number of patients to study in clinical trials in each relevant age

507
00:30:00.440 --> 00:30:00.670
group.

508
00:30:01.740 --> 00:30:05.550
For early trials in particular, additional safeguards for children in clinical

509
00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:07.980
investigations are required by law.

510
00:30:08.060 --> 00:30:11.880
In general, pediatric oncology clinical investigations are considered to involve

511
00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:15.670
greater than minimal risk to children, but also present the prospect of

512
00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:17.660
direct benefit to individual subjects.

513
00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:21.840
For these types of investigations, the Code of Federal Regulations

514
00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:25.720
requires that these risks be justified by the anticipated benefit to the

515
00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:29.610
subjects. The relation of the anticipated benefit to the risk is

516
00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:33.120
at least as favorable to the subjects as that presented by available

517
00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:36.520
alternative approaches, and adequate provisions should be made for

518
00:30:36.580 --> 00:30:40.460
soliciting the assent of pediatric patients and the

519
00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:42.740
permission of their parents or guardians.

520
00:30:43.780 --> 00:30:47.750
Finally, given the cost associated with clinical trial conduct, there is usually

521
00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:51.760
insufficient financial incentive for the pharmaceutical industry to support early

522
00:30:51.860 --> 00:30:53.570
phase pediatric oncology development.

523
00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:58.130
I will discuss some legislation that was enacted to at least partially address this

524
00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:01.140
challenge in pediatric oncology later on in my presentation.

525
00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:06.080
Due to these and other considerations, initial trials in pediatric patients

526
00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:09.820
for many drugs are typically conducted years later than adults and

527
00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:12.020
often after the drug is already approved for adults.

528
00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:16.180
But through the dedicated efforts of many collaborators here and across the

529
00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:20.110
government, academia, industry, and patient advocacy, these challenges are

530
00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:21.760
being addressed in many different ways.

531
00:31:24.580 --> 00:31:28.490
I'm now going to talk about adolescent patients in adult oncology trial because

532
00:31:28.520 --> 00:31:31.550
adolescent patients represent a pediatric age group for which additional

533
00:31:31.620 --> 00:31:35.500
considerations for inclusion in early phase trials apply, namely

534
00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:39.200
when adult oncology clinical trials are being conducted in the

535
00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:40.840
adolescent disease of interest.

536
00:31:42.500 --> 00:31:46.360
FDA's guidance for industry on inclusion of adolescent patients in adult

537
00:31:46.460 --> 00:31:50.120
oncology clinical trials states that adolescent patients should be

538
00:31:50.180 --> 00:31:53.760
eligible for enrollment at all stages of drug development when the

539
00:31:53.780 --> 00:31:57.620
histology and biologic behavior of the cancer under investigation

540
00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:01.220
is the same in, or the molecular target of the drug is

541
00:32:01.229 --> 00:32:04.380
relevant to, cancers in both adults and adolescent

542
00:32:04.420 --> 00:32:07.980
patients. The guidance indicates that generally, first in

543
00:32:08.020 --> 00:32:11.900
human or dose escalation trials should include adolescents after some

544
00:32:11.940 --> 00:32:15.449
initial adult pharmacokinetic and toxicity data are obtained

545
00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:19.540
and should be enrolling patients with relapsed or refractory cancers.

546
00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:23.280
However, depending on the rarity of the disease and the unmet medical need,

547
00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:27.600
as well as experience with the drug or drug class, the FDA teams

548
00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:31.060
may exercise flexibility on how much data constitutes some.

549
00:32:31.900 --> 00:32:35.620
For activity estimating or confirmatory trials, adolescents should be enrolled

550
00:32:35.680 --> 00:32:37.140
simultaneously with adults.

551
00:32:39.740 --> 00:32:43.640
These considerations for adolescents in adult oncology trials are supported by the

552
00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:47.600
knowledge that systemic exposure and clearance of drugs is generally similar

553
00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:51.280
between the two groups. Selection of an appropriate dose for adolescent

554
00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:55.360
patients should be based on the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic

555
00:32:55.500 --> 00:32:59.240
characteristics of the investigational drug, with consideration of body size

556
00:32:59.300 --> 00:33:03.100
effect on drug exposure, toxicity, and activity data if

557
00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:06.930
available, the therapeutic index of the drug, and dose and

558
00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:09.110
exposure response relationship in adults.

559
00:33:09.720 --> 00:33:13.380
For drugs with body size adjusted dosing, adolescents should receive the

560
00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:15.680
same body size adjusted dose as adults.

561
00:33:16.300 --> 00:33:20.080
For drugs administered as a fixed dose in adults, a minimum

562
00:33:20.100 --> 00:33:23.380
body weight threshold should be defined, which is generally 40 kilograms.

563
00:33:23.920 --> 00:33:27.669
Adolescents who weigh at least 40 kilograms may receive the same fixed dose as

564
00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:31.630
adults, and those who weigh less than 40 kilograms should revert to body size

565
00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:35.520
adjusted dosing. For adolescents in adult trials, the study

566
00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:39.470
safety monitoring plan should include long-term follow-up of potential

567
00:33:39.480 --> 00:33:41.420
developmental toxicities when applicable.

568
00:33:44.380 --> 00:33:47.940
The same ethical considerations that apply to early phase pediatric clinical

569
00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:51.600
trials also apply to adult clinical trials that enroll adolescent

570
00:33:51.940 --> 00:33:55.700
patients. Institutional review boards must ensure that the provisions

571
00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:59.260
of 21 CFR 50.52, shown here, are

572
00:33:59.280 --> 00:34:01.050
satisfied before approving the studies.

573
00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:05.320
Considerations should include disease and/or molecular target, available

574
00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:08.899
therapeutic options, and dose level for first-in-human trials.

575
00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:12.519
However, enrollment of appropriately selected adolescent

576
00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:16.350
patients in relevant adult oncology clinical trials with appropriate

577
00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:20.120
dose considerations and adequate safety monitoring is justified

578
00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:23.140
given the severe and life-threatening nature of their disease.

579
00:34:25.220 --> 00:34:28.740
Beyond the specific case of adolescents in adult oncology clinical trials, there

580
00:34:28.761 --> 00:34:32.261
are some early phase trial design elements which may facilitate drug

581
00:34:32.310 --> 00:34:34.801
development for the rest of pediatric oncology.

582
00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:38.920
Each of these elements on the slide here could really individually comprise an

583
00:34:38.940 --> 00:34:39.821
entire session,

584
00:34:40.720 --> 00:34:44.480
but I have listed some different considerations for trial designs for early phase

585
00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:48.281
pediatric clinical trials that may facilitate development in these rare patient

586
00:34:48.301 --> 00:34:52.120
populations. Pediatric oncology clinical trials, as

587
00:34:52.240 --> 00:34:55.761
with adult trials, are often thought of as representing distinct

588
00:34:55.821 --> 00:34:59.240
phases of development, each with separate goals and endpoints.

589
00:34:59.740 --> 00:35:03.380
The earliest phase trials are often considered insufficient to support a

590
00:35:03.420 --> 00:35:07.320
regulatory evaluation for safety and effectiveness, as their goal

591
00:35:07.440 --> 00:35:11.380
is to identify toxicities and a safe dose of the investigational drug to move

592
00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:15.100
forward. However, the design and initiation of every new

593
00:35:15.140 --> 00:35:18.680
clinical trial requires time and resources, which may be

594
00:35:18.720 --> 00:35:22.520
mitigated by seamless designs that incorporate adaptive elements

595
00:35:22.620 --> 00:35:25.470
and support clinical and regulatory decision making.

596
00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:29.920
Moving from dose finding to dose expansion with an efficacy endpoint in the

597
00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:33.840
same trial, particularly in diseases where go, no-go thresholds are

598
00:35:33.900 --> 00:35:37.620
agreed upon, could yield a data set that is suitable for regulatory

599
00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:41.630
submission and marketing authorization, even if the trial is considered early

600
00:35:41.740 --> 00:35:45.344
phase.Furthermore, early clinical trials which

601
00:35:45.384 --> 00:35:49.144
include dose escalation may be expedited by rational dose selection

602
00:35:49.164 --> 00:35:52.884
approaches, which may include PK or exposure-guided dose levels

603
00:35:52.944 --> 00:35:56.284
rather than traditionally identified starting doses that risk being

604
00:35:56.324 --> 00:35:59.534
ineffective, model-informed drug development approaches,

605
00:35:59.944 --> 00:36:03.604
interpatient dose escalation, and early introduction of combination

606
00:36:03.664 --> 00:36:07.264
regimens. We understand that adoption of these elements adds

607
00:36:07.284 --> 00:36:10.804
complexity to an already very complicated disease space, and

608
00:36:10.844 --> 00:36:13.344
recommend early engagement with the FDA.

609
00:36:13.354 --> 00:36:17.114
There are a variety of formal meeting mechanisms that can begin at the

610
00:36:17.144 --> 00:36:20.924
pre-clinical stage and provide support and collaboration throughout the entire

611
00:36:21.024 --> 00:36:21.804
development cycle.

612
00:36:23.864 --> 00:36:27.724
One such scenario that benefits from early engagement with the FDA is when an

613
00:36:27.804 --> 00:36:31.494
academic or industry sponsor is planning a first-in-human trial in

614
00:36:31.504 --> 00:36:35.144
pediatric patients with cancer. Although there is no formal FDA

615
00:36:35.244 --> 00:36:38.684
guidance addressing this topic, in general, if an investigational

616
00:36:38.784 --> 00:36:42.424
product that is solely intended for pediatric cancer that does not

617
00:36:42.544 --> 00:36:45.864
also occur in adults, first-in-human studies in children are

618
00:36:45.904 --> 00:36:47.824
justified on a case-to-case basis.

619
00:36:48.484 --> 00:36:52.454
When evaluating each case, we consider the type of cancer and

620
00:36:52.484 --> 00:36:56.044
the intended patient population, the strength of the pre-clinical data,

621
00:36:56.524 --> 00:37:00.164
the nature of the therapy and route of administration, and often recommend

622
00:37:00.324 --> 00:37:03.924
staged enrollment by age when reasonable within pediatric age

623
00:37:03.984 --> 00:37:07.664
groups. It is important to emphasize the impact of strong

624
00:37:07.784 --> 00:37:11.764
pre-clinical data supporting the drug's mechanism of action and pre-clinical

625
00:37:11.884 --> 00:37:15.324
activity in the specific pediatric cancer planned for clinical

626
00:37:15.364 --> 00:37:18.794
investigation to provide a rationale for initiation of a

627
00:37:18.864 --> 00:37:22.564
first-in-human trial. Given that clinical context varies widely

628
00:37:22.614 --> 00:37:26.524
across the spectrum of pediatric cancer types and therapies, these

629
00:37:26.564 --> 00:37:30.424
study plans should be discussed early at the pre-IND stage with the appropriate

630
00:37:30.544 --> 00:37:31.994
FDA review division.

631
00:37:33.624 --> 00:37:36.944
Finally, I will give you a brief overview of the legislation that affects pediatric

632
00:37:37.004 --> 00:37:40.924
oncology drug development, and provide some incentives and requirements

633
00:37:40.964 --> 00:37:44.784
to facilitate both early phase clinical trials and the entire development programs

634
00:37:44.844 --> 00:37:46.204
through marketing authorization.

635
00:37:47.804 --> 00:37:51.603
Congress initially passed the Best Pharmaceuticals for Children Act, or BPCA, in

636
00:37:51.724 --> 00:37:55.304
2002, and the Pediatric Research Equity Act, or

637
00:37:55.344 --> 00:37:58.613
PREA, in 2003, and these were each made permanent in 2012.

638
00:37:59.144 --> 00:38:02.904
Under BPCA, sponsors of certain marketing applications and

639
00:38:02.944 --> 00:38:06.854
supplements can obtain an additional six months of marketing exclusivity if

640
00:38:06.884 --> 00:38:10.384
the sponsor voluntarily submits information responding to a written

641
00:38:10.444 --> 00:38:14.004
request issued by the FDA relating to the use of a drug in a pediatric

642
00:38:14.044 --> 00:38:17.564
population. Under PREA, sponsors of certain marketing

643
00:38:17.644 --> 00:38:21.204
applications and supplements are required to submit pediatric assessments unless

644
00:38:21.264 --> 00:38:24.084
they receive an applicable waiver or deferral of this requirement.

645
00:38:24.664 --> 00:38:28.464
PREA requirements are triggered by the submission of an application or supplement

646
00:38:28.504 --> 00:38:32.184
for a new active ingredient, new indication, new dosage form, new dosing

647
00:38:32.224 --> 00:38:34.824
regimen, or new route of administration.

648
00:38:34.884 --> 00:38:38.494
However, prior to 2020, PREA had little or no effect on

649
00:38:38.494 --> 00:38:42.104
oncology because most applications for adult cancer drugs were exempt,

650
00:38:42.424 --> 00:38:45.904
due either to their orphan drug designation or because the pediatric study

651
00:38:45.944 --> 00:38:49.924
requirement was waived based on the adult cancer indication, which did not occur

652
00:38:49.944 --> 00:38:53.244
in pediatrics. In 2017, the FDA

653
00:38:53.344 --> 00:38:57.184
Reauthorization Act, or FDARA, amended PREA under the RACE for

654
00:38:57.204 --> 00:39:01.014
Children Act to require pediatric investigations of certain targeted

655
00:39:01.064 --> 00:39:05.004
cancer drugs with new active ingredients based on molecular mechanism of

656
00:39:05.124 --> 00:39:07.184
action rather than clinical indication.

657
00:39:07.644 --> 00:39:11.564
Specifically, if the drug is directed at a molecular target FDA determines to

658
00:39:11.584 --> 00:39:15.184
be substantially relevant to the growth or progression of a pediatric

659
00:39:15.244 --> 00:39:15.644
cancer.

660
00:39:17.384 --> 00:39:21.044
More recently, the Mikayla Nilon Give Kids a Chance Act was signed into law in

661
00:39:21.084 --> 00:39:23.994
February 2026 after unanimous passage by the House of

662
00:39:24.024 --> 00:39:27.974
Representatives. This bill modifies the FDARA requirements relating

663
00:39:28.004 --> 00:39:31.764
to molecularly targeted pediatric cancer investigations to require

664
00:39:31.774 --> 00:39:35.634
research on new drugs used in combination with active ingredients that

665
00:39:35.724 --> 00:39:39.024
have already been approved and that, one, have been determined to be part of the

666
00:39:39.084 --> 00:39:42.864
standard of care for treating a pediatric cancer, or, two, have been approved to

667
00:39:42.904 --> 00:39:46.704
treat an adult cancer and are directed at molecular targets for

668
00:39:46.724 --> 00:39:50.654
pediatric cancer. It also renews FDA's authority to

669
00:39:50.684 --> 00:39:54.524
issue priority review vouchers to sponsors of new products to treat rare

670
00:39:54.624 --> 00:39:58.544
pediatric diseases, a substantial incentive, through September

671
00:39:58.684 --> 00:39:59.304
2029.

672
00:40:00.963 --> 00:40:04.564
Finally, our global colleagues are essential to assuring alignment on pediatric

673
00:40:04.604 --> 00:40:08.434
oncology drug development to increase equitable access to new therapies

674
00:40:08.464 --> 00:40:12.384
across international lines. The pediatric cancer community is well accustomed to

675
00:40:12.404 --> 00:40:15.954
working with colleagues from all over the world to reduce duplicative studies in

676
00:40:15.964 --> 00:40:17.894
the face of limited patient resources.

677
00:40:17.904 --> 00:40:21.514
And likewise, the FDA has frequent interactions with the EMA and other

678
00:40:21.604 --> 00:40:25.334
global regulatory agencies, both formally through common commentaries and

679
00:40:25.404 --> 00:40:28.344
Project Orbis, to name two, and informally.

680
00:40:28.864 --> 00:40:32.484
International consortia are critical when discussing early and late-phase trials

681
00:40:32.524 --> 00:40:34.004
for these rare populations.

682
00:40:34.964 --> 00:40:38.124
So the key takeaways for me are that regulatory

683
00:40:38.164 --> 00:40:42.064
evaluations for first-in-child studies consider the age of the patient, the type

684
00:40:42.104 --> 00:40:46.004
of cancer, existing adult and/or pre-clinical data, and the mechanism of

685
00:40:46.104 --> 00:40:47.904
action of the investigational drug.

686
00:40:47.924 --> 00:40:51.664
There are many ways to facilitate early pediatric oncology drug development through

687
00:40:51.724 --> 00:40:55.603
innovative study design and approaches, and we at the FDA really encourage

688
00:40:55.964 --> 00:40:58.984
frequent interaction to discuss these approaches.

689
00:40:59.004 --> 00:41:02.634
There have been some recent legislation that addresses pediatric drug

690
00:41:02.684 --> 00:41:05.984
development through regulatory requirements and financial incentives.

691
00:41:06.284 --> 00:41:09.984
And as I think we all agree, pediatric oncology drug development should always be

692
00:41:09.994 --> 00:41:13.824
thoughtfully designed for children, and we at the FDA consider it

693
00:41:13.904 --> 00:41:17.244
also important to discuss these development programs early with us.

694
00:41:18.084 --> 00:41:21.844
I want to acknowledge the panel, and the entire wonderful team working in

695
00:41:21.864 --> 00:41:23.984
pediatric oncology at the FDA. Thank you.

696
00:41:35.424 --> 00:41:36.164
All right.

697
00:41:38.544 --> 00:41:42.464
Good afternoon, everyone. It is a real pleasure and a

698
00:41:42.484 --> 00:41:45.544
privilege to be here, and I thank AACR and the organizers

699
00:41:46.264 --> 00:41:48.944
for including me in this wonderful session.

700
00:41:49.004 --> 00:41:51.603
And thanks to my panelists for setting the stage.

701
00:41:52.484 --> 00:41:56.336
SoMy title is Planning for Success, and I think all of us

702
00:41:56.396 --> 00:41:58.976
enter into this hoping for success.

703
00:41:59.036 --> 00:42:02.336
And I'm really going to build on the wonderful example

704
00:42:02.936 --> 00:42:06.386
that Dr. McKeon presented of Revumenib and the

705
00:42:06.496 --> 00:42:10.416
challenges, and really focus this on the development of

706
00:42:10.476 --> 00:42:12.956
oral agents. I have no disclosures.

707
00:42:13.576 --> 00:42:16.396
I'll review some key features, and I will present

708
00:42:17.156 --> 00:42:20.936
additional examples of small molecules that actually

709
00:42:21.016 --> 00:42:24.336
have successfully attained approval across the age continuum,

710
00:42:24.876 --> 00:42:28.786
not all of those simultaneously with the initial approval, but--

711
00:42:29.056 --> 00:42:32.876
And this is not exhaustive, these are just examples to highlight key points,

712
00:42:33.256 --> 00:42:36.576
discuss key learnings from these examples, and offer suggestions.

713
00:42:37.136 --> 00:42:41.036
So you saw this from Dr. Erwin, but this is really still

714
00:42:41.076 --> 00:42:44.976
the landscape, is we really are

715
00:42:44.996 --> 00:42:48.796
lagging behind, and in almost every case, the

716
00:42:48.856 --> 00:42:49.976
adult development

717
00:42:51.056 --> 00:42:54.416
precedes the pediatric oncology development.

718
00:42:55.176 --> 00:42:59.056
We also are faced with really low incidence that

719
00:42:59.196 --> 00:43:02.416
require, as Dr. Dresner highlighted,

720
00:43:02.816 --> 00:43:04.816
multi-center, multidisciplinary trials.

721
00:43:05.736 --> 00:43:07.036
We have to

722
00:43:08.076 --> 00:43:11.046
be focused on the goal of improving outcomes,

723
00:43:11.876 --> 00:43:15.376
and we really require the integration of biology, and we

